commit_message:
Fix for resource polling warnings

When neutron services are disabled,
neutron client logs the 404 exception
at warn level, this exception log
is unwanted and it suffices to log
just the error message.

Change-Id: I7ad8f43eacc9cfa9c66c424ab7ce3a05df5d2fa6
Closes-Bug: 1499403

In VMAX iSCSI driver, the iscsi_ip_address was hardcoded
in cinder.conf. This may have issues with multi-portgroup
environment. If a customer has multiple portgroups
containing different ports with different iSCSI IP addresses,
then ‘iscsiadm‘ command cannot use more than the one hardcoded
IP address in its sendtargets operation.

This patch addresses this by examining the ports in the
portgroup of the masking view used in the attach operation.
Each port has a corresponding iSCSI IP address. A portgroup
with only one port will have one IP address; a portgroup with
multiple ports will have multiple IP addresses. Even if there
is more than one IP address, the first in the list is likely to
result in a successful iscsiadm -sendtargets.

'}]
commit_message:
VMAX Target iSCSI IP Address

In VMAX iSCSI driver, the iscsi_ip_address was hardcoded
in cinder.conf. This may have issues with multi-portgroup
environment. If a customer has multiple portgroups
containing different ports with different iSCSI IP addresses,
then ‘iscsiadm‘ command cannot use more than the one hardcoded
IP address in its sendtargets operation.

This patch addresses this by examining the ports in the
portgroup of the masking view used in the attach operation.
Each port has a corresponding iSCSI IP address. A portgroup
with only one port will have one IP address; a portgroup with
multiple ports will have multiple IP addresses. Even if there
is more than one IP address, the first in the list is likely to
result in a successful iscsiadm -sendtargets.

Closes-Bug: #1501678
Change-Id: I52ab6b278a114d55aec5e66b38ff76fd1bfb1b49

commit_message:
Keep py3.X compatibility for urllib

Use six.moves.urllib.parse instead of urllib.
For urllib2 compatibility, it need to sync policy
module from oslo first. Then six.moves.urllib.request
can replace urllib2.

Partial-Bug: #1280105

Change-Id: I1d4130731c0c506ed4b55ae4ca4b7157a5e8ea60

commit_message:
Delete orphaned instance files from compute nodes

While resizing/revert-resizing instance, if instance gets deleted
in between, then instance files remains either on the source or
destination compute node.

To address this issue, added a new periodic task
'_cleanup_incomplete_migrations' which takes care of deleting
instance files from source/destination compute nodes and then
mark migration record as failed so that it doesn't appear again
in the next periodic task run.

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/manager.py
	nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_mgr.py

SecurityImpact
Closes-Bug: 1392527
Change-Id: I9866d8e32e99b9f907921f4b226edf7b62bd83a7
(cherry picked from commit 18d6b5cc79973fc553daf7a92f22cce4dc0ca013)

commit_message:
Admin_state_up tempest test for health monitor

Use test scenario methods to do admin_state_up tempest test for health monitor.
Here are 3 methods:
1.test_create_health_monitor_with_scenarios
2.test_update_health_monitor_state_up_true_with_scenarios
3.test_update_health_monitor_state_up_false_with_scenarios

Added the base class as a dependency.

For each method, we need to test 16 secnarios, since we need to set admin_state_up
status for loadbalancer, listener, pool, health monitor, each has true and false status.
we setup the resources in the setup method, method validation is to check if the status
for admin_state_up is correctly setup or not.


Change-Id: I33b82ec550e7c876dbf2d0751054ff488b658e26

commit_message:
Do not log an error when deleting a linuxbridge does not exist

When you're racing to teardown and relying on RPC, it should not be
considered an error that a bridge does not exist when you're trying to
delete it anyway. This is better served as debug level information.

For context, this shows up over 1000 times in successful
gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-linuxbridge job runs in a week so it's
probably safe to say it's not contributing to test failures.

Closes-Bug: #1501779

Change-Id: I8e9b27e010d033291497f4e660a97bbae92e75b1
(cherry picked from commit a9dc48f5a4616a505824c3e8520c3dce7436f1b1)

commit_message:
Download forbidden when get_image_location is set.

When using v2 an attempt to download an image would return a 403 if the
get_image_location policy was set.

Note: We had been returning both 404 and 204 when no data was
available. There was no way to detect the 404 case without trying to
access the image locations so I've standardized on 204.

Change-Id: I658b08a35d3a8cb8a7096baf716ccb3d6e7d9abf
Closes-bug: 1501672

The default bind_port (6011-6013) in the sample config files for swift
use port numbers that are in the range registered by X11 (6000-6063) and
can prevent swift from starting if the ports are in use.

Closes-Bug: #1254328
'}]
commit_message:
Change the default bind_port for swift

The default bind_port (6011-6013) in the sample config files for swift
use port numbers that are in the range registered by X11 (6000-6063) and
can prevent swift from starting if the ports are in use.

We should use an unregistered range (6611-6613).

Change-Id: Ifd95b99004aead5ddc8ae1a8dd3ccd9c4f2abe91
Closes-Bug: #1254328

commit_message:
Add LimitRequestBody to sample httpd config

Web servers that are exposed to the Internet eventually gain a
security feature of limiting the amount of data in the request
body. In Apache Httpd, this is provided by the LimitRequestBody
directive. This is added to the sample Httpd config file.

The limit is set for only the keystone services so it won't
affect other services running in Httpd.

The value of 114688 was picked because it's the current limit
on request body that oslo.middleware's sizelimit function puts
on requests to keystone.

Use of oslo.middleware's sizelimit re-implementation can be
deprecated.

Docs:
- http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/mod/core.html#limitrequestbody

ReleaseNotesImpact

Closes-Bug: 1481048
Change-Id: I5509e4b65900c15dd0b5fda43b1d5bb4dc3ff5ff

commit_message:
Removed full path from conf file reference

In the original text, the full path was shown, which was incorrect for some
distros. Patch 231028 gave distro-specific paths, but we do not give
distro-specific information in this guide, and that patch has been reverted.
This patch fixes the original text to remove the full path, and replace it
with the name of the config file only.

Change-Id: I65726323ca15e53dc8d25a4e93627dfc6005cb46
Closes-bug: #1502927

commit_message:
Large Containers - container sharding spec

This is a new version of the container sharding spec. This time
it focuses entirely on the Distributed Prefix Tree (trie) version.

I will coninue tweaking the code in the POC as such there may
be a few more patchsets of this spec before the summit.

commit_message:
Update sharding spec, notably CountingTrie and shrinking

Updates to the sharding spec:
 - Root container short circuting
 - CoutingTrie and changes to finding suitable candidates and misplaced
   items.
 - Shard container auditing
 - Shrinking (collapsing) sharded containers (V1).

Change-Id: I5be0cfa240455a831d472e00c811c5e103bf60d3

commit_message:
Refactor list_all_block_devices & add block_type param

Put the columns to retrieve from lsblk into a list so that future
modifications to columns will require fewer code changes.

Also add a 'block_type' parameter which defaults to 'disk'. To make the
function more flexible if callers wanted a different block type.

Update and add unit tests

subject: ASG scaling account for cooldown timestamp & in-progress
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2015-10-02 00:33:08.000000000', 'files': ['heat/engine/resources/autoscaling.py', 'heat/engine/resources/openstack/scaling_policy.py', 'heat/tests/test_autoscaling.py', 'heat/tests/test_heat_autoscaling_group.py', 'heat/scaling/cooldown.py', 'heat/engine/resources/aws/scaling_policy.py'], 'message': 'ASG scaling account for cooldown timestamp & in-progress

There are cases where it takes a long time to create a new resource as
requested by the scaling operation on an ASG resource, for instance, a
nova server creation followed by a complex SoftwareDeployment. During
this process, additional alarms may come in but failed to be blocked
by the current cooldown checking mechanism because the very first
timestamp has yet to be generated. This is leading to unexpected size
adjustment to the ASG.

This patch augments the existing cooldown checking mechanism with a
scaling-in-progress test so that additional alarms arriving during
the very first scaling operation will be ignored.

Change-Id: I93eae99baa4a33ad0b1d34a6eb0aacb2ac5ddfa3
Closes-Bug: #1375156
'}]
commit_message:
ASG scaling account for cooldown timestamp & in-progress

There are cases where it takes a long time to create a new resource as
requested by the scaling operation on an ASG resource, for instance, a
nova server creation followed by a complex SoftwareDeployment. During
this process, additional alarms may come in but failed to be blocked
by the current cooldown checking mechanism because the very first
timestamp has yet to be generated. This is leading to unexpected size
adjustment to the ASG.

This patch augments the existing cooldown checking mechanism with a
scaling-in-progress test so that additional alarms arriving during
the very first scaling operation will be ignored.

Change-Id: I93eae99baa4a33ad0b1d34a6eb0aacb2ac5ddfa3
Closes-Bug: #1375156

commit_message:
Fix translating for props with get_param value

If some map or list type properties specified with
json-type or commadelimitedlist parameters, error
raised in case of wrong properties data parsing.
Fix this case by adding check if data is GetParam
instance, resolve it. Other function can be safely
replaced without resolve.

Change-Id: I0c9a6af29b56b629cbdad2acb868c3033e38b5ef
Closes-bug: #1494364
(cherry picked from commit aea59ecdac6ed6635125eb2064554140e3e645fc)

subject: Provide option to delete floating IP with server
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2015-10-06 19:18:35.000000000', 'files': ['shade/__init__.py'], 'message': "Provide option to delete floating IP with server

Although the only real reason you should need a floating IP are for
the cases where you want an IP with a lifespan independent from the
server, there are clouds that are insane and require a floating IP
to be created with every server. When a person is deleting that
server, we should ensure that the floating IP is delete. However, it's
impossible to infer intent about whether the floating IP wants to stick
around, so it has to be a flag.

We will default to False because deleting things that the user did not
expect to be deleted is surprising in a bad way.

Change-Id: Id90bdc819ad8f1b04acc1b35788786d23f4e7666
"}]
commit_message:
Provide option to delete floating IP with server

Although the only real reason you should need a floating IP are for
the cases where you want an IP with a lifespan independent from the
server, there are clouds that are insane and require a floating IP
to be created with every server. When a person is deleting that
server, we should ensure that the floating IP is delete. However, it's
impossible to infer intent about whether the floating IP wants to stick
around, so it has to be a flag.

We will default to False because deleting things that the user did not
expect to be deleted is surprising in a bad way.

The 'message' attribute for exceptions has been deprecated since Python
2.6 and does not exist in Python 3. The IronicException 'message'
attribute will still exist (but should not be used) in Python 2.x as the
BaseException class provides it, but in Python 3.x it will no longer
exist.

The preferred way to get a message from an exception is
six.text_type(exc) as this provides the unicode version of the
exception.

This change renames the 'message' attribute to '_msg_fmt' to indicate to

Change-Id: Id080ea42d7ae6337ce23c1411cf4e8a903223d3d

commit_message:
Rename 'message' attribute to '_msg_fmt' in IronicException

The 'message' attribute for exceptions has been deprecated since Python
2.6 and does not exist in Python 3. The IronicException 'message'
attribute will still exist (but should not be used) in Python 2.x as the
BaseException class provides it, but in Python 3.x it will no longer
exist.

The preferred way to get a message from an exception is
six.text_type(exc) as this provides the unicode version of the
exception.

This change renames the 'message' attribute to '_msg_fmt' to indicate to
users that they should not use it directly.

For any third-party users of the IronicException class, log a warning
that usage of the 'message' attribute is deprecated, but allow them to
keep working.

This is similar, but different, to work done in Nova:
  commit 70569ae344bceb3794713abc5cb2c82e9671c37d
  Author: Mark McLoughlin <markmc@redhat.com>
  Date:   Mon Jul 1 11:31:06 2013 +0100
  Subject: Avoid shadowing Exception 'message' attribute

Change-Id: Id080ea42d7ae6337ce23c1411cf4e8a903223d3d

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-10-05 09:24:45.000000000', 'files': ['specs/mitaka-template.rst'], 'message': 'template: remove "Project priority" section of spec

The "Project priority" section in the spec template is a source
of persistent confusion and mis-use. A large portion of spec
authors believe that it is a section to fill with their own
opinions on why their spec is important. In fact, pretty much
all specs should put the words "None" in this section. This is
particularly true earlier in the cycle, since the actual project
priorities do not get finalized / agreed on until the design
summit. Even once the priorities are agreed, this section of
the spec is still fairly pointless, since we've moved to tracking
priority specs in a separate etherpad. eg

  https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/mitaka-nova-priorities-tracking

Just remove this source of confusion since it doesn't serve any
particularly useful purpose anymore, given the external tracking
done.

Change-Id: I808227fe71210abc64270f53ef3d3d62f176ff24
'}]
commit_message:
template: remove "Project priority" section of spec

The "Project priority" section in the spec template is a source
of persistent confusion and mis-use. A large portion of spec
authors believe that it is a section to fill with their own
opinions on why their spec is important. In fact, pretty much
all specs should put the words "None" in this section. This is
particularly true earlier in the cycle, since the actual project
priorities do not get finalized / agreed on until the design
summit. Even once the priorities are agreed, this section of
the spec is still fairly pointless, since we've moved to tracking
priority specs in a separate etherpad. eg

  https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/mitaka-nova-priorities-tracking

Just remove this source of confusion since it doesn't serve any
particularly useful purpose anymore, given the external tracking
done.

Change-Id: I808227fe71210abc64270f53ef3d3d62f176ff24

subject: Replace .iteritems() with .items()
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-10-02 18:00:30.000000000', 'files': ['ironic_lib/exception.py', 'ironic_lib/disk_utils.py'], 'message': "Replace .iteritems() with .items()

As mentioned in the developer's guide[0] and in a discussion[1], we
shouldn't use six.iteritems() unless there's a good reason (eg large
data set).

Since there's no need to use six.iteritems() or dict.iteritems() in the
two places where it is being used, this patch replaces them with
items().

[0] http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#peer-review
[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066391.html

Change-Id: Iaf4ffc755293454a054fff3efffd5a30e1c18fd7
"}]
commit_message:
Replace .iteritems() with .items()

As mentioned in the developer's guide[0] and in a discussion[1], we
shouldn't use six.iteritems() unless there's a good reason (eg large
data set).

Since there's no need to use six.iteritems() or dict.iteritems() in the
two places where it is being used, this patch replaces them with
items().

[0] http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#peer-review
[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066391.html

Change-Id: Iaf4ffc755293454a054fff3efffd5a30e1c18fd7

subject: Correctly filter events on resource name
revisions:
[{'number': 7, 'created': '2015-10-06 16:32:26.000000000', 'files': ['heat/tests/api/openstack_v1/test_events.py', 'heat/api/openstack/v1/events.py'], 'message': 'Correctly filter events on resource name

Filtering on resource name can be accomplished by using the db
filters instead of using a filter method. Furthermore, using a
custom filter breaks certain assumptions made by other parts of
the codebase, which lead to pagination being broken.
Specifically, custom filter for resource name is applied only
after other filtering is finished. As a result, we try to find
result from only 1 event and this event belongs to whole
stack and thus its resource_name is equal to the stack name.
This returns an event not found error instead of returning
the first event assosciated with the resource name.

Change-Id: Ie7d28ffb88a79d6e0f516f0db385be2eed59f7f0
Closes-Bug: #1502751
'}]
commit_message:
Correctly filter events on resource name

Filtering on resource name can be accomplished by using the db
filters instead of using a filter method. Furthermore, using a
custom filter breaks certain assumptions made by other parts of
the codebase, which lead to pagination being broken.
Specifically, custom filter for resource name is applied only
after other filtering is finished. As a result, we try to find
result from only 1 event and this event belongs to whole
stack and thus its resource_name is equal to the stack name.
This returns an event not found error instead of returning
the first event assosciated with the resource name.

Change-Id: Ie7d28ffb88a79d6e0f516f0db385be2eed59f7f0
Closes-Bug: #1502751

subject: Do no net/subnet checks during validate
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-10-06 00:30:07.000000000', 'files': ['heat/tests/nova/test_server.py', 'heat/engine/resources/openstack/nova/server_network_mixin.py'], 'message': "Do no net/subnet checks during validate

Currently validation fails if the network or the subnet are defined in
the same template as the server because they don't exist during
validate.

_validate_belonging_subnet_to_net is called during _build_nics so this
check still happens when the required resources actually exist.

Also, test method validate_internal_port_subnet_not_this_network was not
running because its name was not prefixed with test_. Fixing and
updating this test revealed issues with the validation failed message.

Closes-Bug: #1503060
Change-Id: I2e062abf5b9fb7446b979ba6acc2e2b531d957d6
"}]
commit_message:
Do no net/subnet checks during validate

Currently validation fails if the network or the subnet are defined in
the same template as the server because they don't exist during
validate.

_validate_belonging_subnet_to_net is called during _build_nics so this
check still happens when the required resources actually exist.

Also, test method validate_internal_port_subnet_not_this_network was not
running because its name was not prefixed with test_. Fixing and
updating this test revealed issues with the validation failed message.

Closes-Bug: #1503060
Change-Id: I2e062abf5b9fb7446b979ba6acc2e2b531d957d6

commit_message:
Fix tempest-account-generator command roles issue

The change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/216109 modified the
identity client to return the entire response object instead of
only part of it. This patch fixes a call to list_roles that was
missed in the tempest-account-generator tool.

commit_message:
remove additional service checks for upgrading

Even though you've told grenade to UPGRADE a project, we still go and
check to see if it's enabled in devstack before we believe you. For
components that are fully implemented in the grenade and devstack
trees, this is fine. However for plugins this is weird, because
stackrc doesn't provide enough information to figure this out.

We should not do this second check, just trust your grenade config is
correct. This code was probably vestigial to getting the refactor
working correctly before the kilo release.

Change-Id: I01d00f95d602b9b159b3b64ff46a7cd3e23c3983

commit_message:
Allow updating TLS refs

A bug prevented updating of default_tls_container_ref and failing
with a 503

This bug uncovered a few other issues with null key checks
and complaints if sni_container_refs were not provided.

Change-Id: I636e9f78b38ba9f02d10a013bf56459cc2a723e1
Closes-Bug: #1501505
(cherry picked from commit b8c3978de696786615cd72f90c0858d1032d241b)

subject: Ensure to decode bytes or fail
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2015-10-06 20:31:59.000000000', 'files': ['neutronclient/tests/unit/test_cli20.py'], 'message': "Ensure to decode bytes or fail

The commit fcf289797c063088f9003359dfd1c7d4f41ed5ef introduces the
pattern:

  if isinstance(line, bytes):
    try:
      line = line.decode(encoding='utf-8')
    except UnicodeError:
      pass
  # concat line with a string

which is not working in PY3K if an UnicodeError is raised because line
is not decoded and concatened to a string.

This change delegates decoding to safe_decode[1] which returns a text
object or raises an error.

[1] oslo_utils.encodeutils

Closes-Bug: #1503415
Related-Bug: #1499004
Change-Id: I16b8013f33aa3efad65be8040d3210120e047bbd
"}]
commit_message:
Ensure to decode bytes or fail

The commit fcf289797c063088f9003359dfd1c7d4f41ed5ef introduces the
pattern:

  if isinstance(line, bytes):
    try:
      line = line.decode(encoding='utf-8')
    except UnicodeError:
      pass
  # concat line with a string

which is not working in PY3K if an UnicodeError is raised because line
is not decoded and concatened to a string.

This change delegates decoding to safe_decode[1] which returns a text
object or raises an error.

[1] oslo_utils.encodeutils

Closes-Bug: #1503415
Related-Bug: #1499004
Change-Id: I16b8013f33aa3efad65be8040d3210120e047bbd

commit_message:
Let devstack-gate handle the gate hook timeout

Devstack gate now handles all of the hook timeouts itself so that
individual jobs do not need to reinvent this wheel. Remove the timeout
support from the functional test gate hook here as a result.

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Fix incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected) as below.
  assertEqual(observed, expected) => assertEqual(expected, observed)

Target of this patch:
  manila/tests/cmd/*
  manila/tests/compute/*
  manila/db/*
  manila/network/*

Change-Id: I6dd4f8057facc68e716b57229cbc4096af8bb152
Partial-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Bring Kolla inline with FHS

This brings Kolla images inline with FHS and should make finding
locations of things more consistent and reliable with the linux world
at large.

Change-Id: Iece5b4da4bace0fb8b1f41a65ab2c852ec73e6f8
Closes-Bug: #1485742
(cherry picked from commit 94162bd08f40ec742a7bfcdcd4aac45be5bd5618)

commit_message:
Common start.sh

The majority of the start.sh code is identical. This removes that
duplicate code while still maintaining the ability to call code in a
specific container.

The start.sh is moved into /usr/local/bin/kolla_start in the container

The extend_start.sh script is called by the kolla_start script at the
location /usr/local/bin/kolla_extend_start . It always exists because
we create a noop kolla_extend_start in the base directory. We override
it with extend_start.sh in a specific image should we need to.

Of note, the neutron-agents container is exempt from this new
structure due to it being a fat container.

Additionally, we fix the inconsistent permissions throughout. 644 for
repo files and the scripts are set to 755 via a Docker RUN command to
ensure someones local perm change won't break upstream containers.

Change-Id: I7da8d19965463ad30ee522a71183e3f092e0d6ad
Closes-Bug: #1501295
(cherry picked from commit cb4e875ae1e1ec2e6ddf8a6b37f42283697fd50c)

commit_message:
verification: set timeout for requests.get when testing for Horizon

The default timeout for requests.get is None. Because of that the
requests.get call will hang forever if no Horizion dashboard is
available.

Change-Id: Ibbe7ff1ada234b6b733be2c29c278f0f0711219d
Closes-bug: #1501696

commit_message:
Gracefully handle non-existent policy on rule insert

Previously, trying to insert a rule into a non-existent policy caused
an internal server error.

This change avoids the internal server error and properly raises
an exception that is surfaced to the user.

Make it possible to use the simpler syntax:

  with client.ignore_not_found:
    client.do_something()

instead of:

  try:
    client.do_something()
  except Exception as ex:
    client.ignore_not_found(ex)

Change-Id: I3620bb97945ff24019c6e51e5e4a453b4f627792

commit_message:
Make ClientPlugin.ignore_not_found a context manager

Make it possible to use the simpler syntax:

  with client.ignore_not_found:
    client.do_something()

instead of:

  try:
    client.do_something()
  except Exception as ex:
    client.ignore_not_found(ex)

The previous syntax is, however, still supported so there is no loss of
backward compatibility.

Change-Id: I3620bb97945ff24019c6e51e5e4a453b4f627792

commit_message:
Add DatasetService to read and manage `config.json`.

The DatasetService is intended to load and manage any number of
configured data sources as specified in `config.json`. It also
enforces use of Angular's built-in content caching to improve
loading times of already-accessed datasets.

Change-Id: Ibb161a171d6375bf024bf8c0ab051c3f1a97f760

commit_message:
Filter get_pool_members to return members from the desired pool

Calls to "neutron lbaas-member-list <pool_id>" are currently returning
all members from every pool, not just those belonging to <pool_id>.
There is no filter being passed to the database query for pool
members.

This fix creates a filter for <pool_id>.

Change-Id: I206e5fca06e2e4322c42737a98a4cfa5c055101e
Closes-Bug: #1483100
Co-Authored-By: Brandon Logan <brandon.logan@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 539c1e8c5b4762a7ab668c47aa212f85aaa4f376)

commit_message:
keystone-533 support internal_endpoint advertisement for version discovery

Piggyback on the existing URL normalizing middleware to correct the
URL coming from internal VIP. This is based on the header

X-Vip-Name: internal

If the given request is a version discovery request and the 'X-Vip-Name' header
is set, we'll fix the outgoing links to reflect the internal VIP.

Change-Id: I41e86ba41c6f67ad5867ef5819570186eb06401b

commit_message:
Clean up Image v2 image set command

Make the Image v2 image set command meet at the intersection of the v1
image set command and the v2 image create command:

* Add visibility to the deadopts list and remove the option
* Put the options in the same order as v1 image set
* Make the help text match
* Add --properties
* Move the additional options that do not appear in either v1 image set or
  v2 image create after --property as they are really pre-defined properties
* Add tests for v2 image set to match v1 and then some
* Put the SetImage class in v2/image.py in alphabetical order

Change-Id: I102b914e8ad09a014f6fdd846c5766b6c2eaadb8

commit_message:
Add manage_existing and unmanage to BaseVD

manage_existing() and unmanage() only exist in the deprecated
VolumeDriver() class and not BaseVD.  This means that drivers
inheriting from *VD hit attribute errors when trying to call
either of these methods.

Related-Bug: #1478987
Related-Bug: #1493286
Related-Bug: #1471807
Closes-Bug: #1487329

Change-Id: Ie8aba971b51e1f5eaac5a4e681ea06b358ebb7b8

The Public cloud load has a 20K iteration for each tenant and metric.
This is wrong and it will generate 30M messages.
The correct value is 5K and it will generate the expected 7.5M.

Also added documentation reflecting the changes in the code to
suppor tenant_id, resource_id and date.

'}]
commit_message:
Correct the Public Cloud Simulation load

The Public cloud load has a 20K iteration for each tenant and metric.
This is wrong and it will generate 30M messages.
The correct value is 5K and it will generate the expected 7.5M.

Also added documentation reflecting the changes in the code to
suppor tenant_id, resource_id and date.

Added documentation on how to set the system to deal with high load.

Change-Id: I9ca24cb46828b2a225bb61f720e54b55edb65571

commit_message:
Fix args parsing for quota-class-update

Change 'class-name' argument to 'class_name' to avoid
AttributeError.

Add alias '--share_network' to command-line args.

Add argument 'snapshot_gigabytes' to 'update' function of
QuotaClassSetManager.

Closes-bug: #1498457

commit_message:
Pass bay_ident to k8s objects methods

Pass bay_ident to k8s objects (pod, service, replication controllers)
list method. Doing so returns a list of k8s objects based on the
specified bay identifier. A Bay identifier can be an UUID or a logical
name of the Bay.

magnum rc-list => magnum rc-list <bay_ident>

magnum service-list => magnum service-list <bay_ident>

magnum pod-list => magnum pod-list <bay_ident>

Change-Id: Ia1ec5376d728a4eaacf344cbda5c60d80fbb0495
Closes-Bug: #1503066

commit_message:
Note that the TC expects some project history.

The recent application by the Kosmos project [1] prompted a discussion
on whether or not a project should apply to the TC right away or if it
should have some amount of history of operating as an OpenStack project
first.  The consensus on that application was that we should wait and
let the project get going first.

This patch updates the new projects requirements to clarify this point.
As noted by ttx on [1], this guideline will henceforth be known as
"the Kosmos jurisprudence".

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/223674/

Change-Id: Ifc964d09ea2107e3ecd95f9579543bcb77f457d0
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
stackforge retirement: make workflow reqs+cla clearer

There has been some concern voiced over the ambiguity of the language
used in this resolution. Concerns were brought up about whether new or
existing contributors will now need to sign a CLA or alter workflow. It
is my understanding that this is not the case.

To make this clear, I propose adding this unambiguous writing to the
resolution.

Change-Id: Iac0f87678479e694350cccfb9bb87ce3bb946ff6

commit_message:
Fix VMAX live migration problem

Live migration fails for VMAX because the host is not taken into
account when determining whether a volume is masked or not. For
live migration it is necessary to know which host a volume is masked
to. This patch fixes the problem by checking which host the volume
is masked to.

Change-Id: I693e29f7b26145bd1fd357b7d98377e26bfdfed8
Closes-Bug: #1498964
(cherry picked from commit 794e27c78255c94084b54821d44a36fd8f2096d7)

commit_message:
encapsulate running rspec-system

Instead of being inlined on the machine running rspec-system, the script
is in the repository. This gives control on its execution to code
contributors instead of just the person with access to the machine
running vagrant.

Change-Id: I6649a82c21477a97cc932f12c287f2d1db4c04c5
Signed-off-by: Loic Dachary <loic@dachary.org>

commit_message:
rework rspec-system machines and sets

Running tests in parallel requires that each run happen in a different
machine. Instead of defining the 'first' and 'second' machine which,
define a different machine (or machines) for each test in the
.nodeset.yml

The rspec-system files are reworked to remove hardcoded 'first' and
'second' as well as hard coded IPs.

Change-Id: Idd871633b284a8601d738fa37c2c087abedf7a5f
Signed-off-by: Loic Dachary <loic@dachary.org>

commit_message:
Added matchmaker timeouts and retries

Fixed and restored previously skipped test CallTestCase.test_timeout
_connect_to_host() and get_single_hosts() now accept optional timeout
parameter.
_connect_to_host() accepts optional retry parameter
If timeout value (in seconds) is greater than 0, the connection attempts
will be retried $retry times with a specified timeout.

Change-Id: I1c897d917d0defda581b8ff62e7a67e32f011fee
Closes-Bug: #1499713

commit_message:
Fix rpc code due to neutron changes

The following commit: I6fea7f409c91b25d2c35b038d6100fdfa85d1905
Merged into neutron which changed how the rpc workers are started.
This patch updates the ovn plugin so that dhcp and other services
that depend on neutrons rpcs work again. It also refactors the code
a little bit to be more modular.

Change-Id: Ia217465abb2b21100cca0e75de3bbaf4a6aee56d
Depends-on: I31981e905f892df474c57b45d3e70ebfbeeae1db
Closes-bug: #1503072

commit_message:
Leverage metadata.json to install the module

We are effectively duplicating dependency declaration across
Puppetfile, fixtures.yml, metadata.json as well as in the
beaker spec_helper.

This commit has two primary benefits:
- It leverages the already standard metadata.json to resolve
and install dependencies instead of duplicating them here
- It tests that the package build and installation works for
publishing eventually in the forge.

Change-Id: I901ce131b8966b7838a84a55c9686570bd223b46

commit_message:
Add volume type to create server API

Currently in create server API, using block_device_mapping
parameter can create cinder volume and attach to instance, but there
aren't volume type parameter to create a SLA based volume, so
this bp will add the volume type to create api.

Change-Id: I6289203860130c3f002adb212ceaef2952f12ecb
Blueprint: enable-volume-types

commit_message:
Add missing calls to Identity admin API v2.0

This patch addresses the missing "create user" and
"list users" calls (/v2.0/users) in the bug, but other calls were
also missing and have been added:

- /v2.0/users/{userId}
- /v2.0/tenants
- /v2.0/tenants/{tenantId}

Change-Id: I8cffb1cfdee3f6319eb22c5934cb90559b2eea68
Closes-Bug: #1418538
Closes-Bug: #1499344

commit_message:
Clean up telemetry API v2

Use http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ceilometer/webapi/v2.html#
as the source

Changes:
- renamed createMeter to addSamplesToMeter to better describe it
- Added missing request and response parameters
- Rearranged the methods to mimic other APIs (with delete calls
at the end, and list calls at the beginning)
- Updated code samples to match those on the spec page

Change-Id: I3466c7388509fe66310cd3ab478847a09f6d30b8
Closes-Bug: #1428661

revisions:

A previous patch split the work done by get_openstack_vars into

commit_message:
Add a private method for nodepool server vars

A previous patch split the work done by get_openstack_vars into
costly and less-costly operations.  Nodepool only needs the
less-costly ones.  We will put that information in the shade API
in some form, but it has not been decided what form yet.  In the
mean time, allow Nodepool to easily call the method to perform
the less-costly operations for now.

Change-Id: I99bec7e4a709ef6b7623414dad5f1453070380f8

subject: Split get_hostvars_from_server into two
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-10-05 14:49:13.000000000', 'files': ['shade/meta.py'], 'message': 'Split get_hostvars_from_server into two

There are really two different things going on here. One is figuring
out essential information "what IP do I use to talk to this server"
The other is fleshing out some additional information that is useful
for ansible inventories. The ansible inventory info is expensive when
that's not what you're doing and when you're not using shade-level
caching.

A follow-on patch will make the create/get/list server calls use the
new function always.

Change-Id: Ia1de78d26c708ce6fe3205a9484cb16a92360890
'}]
commit_message:
Split get_hostvars_from_server into two

There are really two different things going on here. One is figuring
out essential information "what IP do I use to talk to this server"
The other is fleshing out some additional information that is useful
for ansible inventories. The ansible inventory info is expensive when
that's not what you're doing and when you're not using shade-level
caching.

A follow-on patch will make the create/get/list server calls use the
new function always.

Change-Id: Ia1de78d26c708ce6fe3205a9484cb16a92360890

commit_message:
Update python-troveclient requirement

Without a version defined, it is possible that an older trove
client may become installed, which may still attempt to utilize
the oslo.utils namespace.

Update the version of the troveclient library to a version after
the oslo namespace change.

Change-Id: I1e1f6043a7c82674312016aea662674675404dd8

commit_message:
Converting compute-hyperv to py3

Initial conversion with 2to3 tool
Added support for Python3
Replaces / with // for Py3 compatibility
Adds Py2.7 compatibility
Fix IOUtils Py3 compatibility issue. The method retrieving
buffer data was raising a TypeError on Py3.

Co-Authored-By: Alessandro Pilotti <apilotti@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Co-Authored-By: Claudiu Belu <cbelu@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Co-Authored-By: Lucian Petrut <lpetrut@cloudbasesolutions.com>

revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2015-10-01 20:59:22.000000000', 'files': ['reno/tests/test_scanner.py', 'reno/formatter.py', 'reno/utils.py'], 'message': 'Handle errors scanning a branch

If a branch does not exist or does not contain any release notes, git
throws an error. Handle the error by returning an empty result set, and
let the formatter report the empty results explicitly in its output.

Change-Id: I80841ac0fd0b2a9de4348460027ed8bdff99b288
'}]
commit_message:
Handle errors scanning a branch

If a branch does not exist or does not contain any release notes, git
throws an error. Handle the error by returning an empty result set, and
let the formatter report the empty results explicitly in its output.

Change-Id: I80841ac0fd0b2a9de4348460027ed8bdff99b288

commit_message:
retry creates/deletes in the pool manager

- The pool manager doesn't retry creates/deletes right away. If there's
just a small net split, or the DNS server has some temporary failure, trying
a second time will usually succeed. This should fix a lot of premature ERROR
states

Change-Id: Ib61110c4e460e93b8b5cfa8a9256151a5cabc43b
closes-bug: #1503350

subject: Do not pass along cidr and ip_version to create_subnet when not used
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-09-30 12:37:55.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_dashboard/api/neutron.py', 'openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/networks/workflows.py'], 'message': 'Do not pass along cidr and ip_version to create_subnet when not used

A recent change in Neutron or netaddr makes it an error to send create_subnet
message with cidr set to None.

This patch updates Horizon code to make the cidr and ip_version parameters

Change-Id: Icd55a3629422d60470182591449cf726d52575a6

commit_message:
Do not pass along cidr and ip_version to create_subnet when not used

A recent change in Neutron or netaddr makes it an error to send create_subnet
message with cidr set to None.

This patch updates Horizon code to make the cidr and ip_version parameters
optional and updates the handling of these values from the subnet create
workflow.

Change-Id: Icd55a3629422d60470182591449cf726d52575a6
Closes-Bug: 1495191
(cherry picked from commit 8064dcc4858d4463626eb795e9bfd97ba66649c9)

commit_message:
Skip validation on nodes in maintenance mode

Currently, the validator runs on nodes that are in maintenance mode,
which in many cases is not the user's desire.

This patch limits the boot validation checks to only nodes that have
maintenance=False

Change-Id: If548371020bdd79750a1d85582072e3c9ac704d0

commit_message:
Validate project with Keystone

The following patch validates a specified project with
Keystone. It is only meant to validate the project ID
for quota management (i.e. quota-show, quota-update) and
in flavor management (i.e. flavor-access-add).

Change-Id: I67b43a8393aab457b90949e02d2025384663eb74
Implements: blueprint validate-project-with-keystone
Closes-Bug: #1317515
Closes-Bug: #1118066
DocImpact

commit_message:
Fix .fixtures.yml for openstack module unit tests

Most of all OpenStack modules were removed from fuel-library
and .fixtures.yml of 'openstack' module wasn't updated according
these changes. That's why unit tests were failing on 'openstack' module.

Change-Id: I845fa8ec9f8f5b0c5d80ba4c8b595d0ded2bc556
Closes-bug: #1503238

commit_message:
Move cinder module to librarian

This commit removes 'cinder' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses 7.0.0-mos-rc1 tag of cinder module.
This tag is intermediate stable state of current master.
Custom patch: https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11038/
it's not merged in upstream yet.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I3ef7e0bb1231db41b6baf1b8d70d8e638519be4a

distro setuptools is old and should never be touched if you're going

commit_message:
Stop using distro setuptools and easy_install

distro setuptools is old and should never be touched if you're going
to install things from pip. easy_install is insecure and open to
MITM attacks.

Downloading get-pip.py over https and running it will install modern
pip and setuptools on the system and is the preferred method for
installing pip in all cases.

Change-Id: I1bf88f018806142ca639f3c183598b318636e61d

commit_message:
Move ceilometer module to librarian

This commit removes 'ceilometer' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses 7.0.0-mos-rc1 tag ceilometer module.
This tag is intermediate stable state of current master.
Ceilometer module doesn't contain custom patches.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I77da42899f7d84bb168206e37aba8cdd7882a691

commit_message:
Move swift module to librarian

This commit removes 'swift' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses 7.0.0-mos-rc2 tag of swift module.
This tag is intermediate stable state of current master.
Custom patch is https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/10992/
it's merged in upstream, will be synced along with
next merge commit from master branch.

Custom patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/198695/ was reworked:
* exec for rebalance should return [0,1] according to bug#1402701;
* create /etc/swift/backups directory from openstack::swift::proxy class
* rebalance exec with pretend-min-part-hours is not needed anymore
  because it's implemented now by swift cron jobs

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: Iffcf470f7772241cade7fac6679712187ef206e4

Move glance module to librarian

This commit removes 'glance' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses 7.0.0-mos-rc1 tag of glance module.
This tag is intermediate stable state of current master.
Glance module doesn't contain custom patches.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

commit_message:
Check if vios_w returned from find_vios

It's possible during VM Migration to fail before the vfc mappings
have been created. If this happens the revert attempts to
remove the mappings, but find_vios_for_vfc_wwpns will return
None because there aren't any mappings.

Change-Id: I717cd998c496c8f66660f03f07b58641d24755d7
Closes-Bug: #1502726
Closes-Bug: #1502892

commit_message:
Activate pep8 check that _ is imported

Remove the specification in tox.ini that _ is a builtin so that
it will no longer assume that _ does not need to be imported.
This helps ensure that the _ from i18n is used.

Activating this check did not flag any violations.

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-10-05 13:52:33.000000000', 'files': ['cinder/volume/driver.py', 'cinder/tests/unit/test_volume.py'], 'message': "Detach volume on device validation failure

If device validation fails when attaching a volume for some driver
operation (copy_volume_data, copy_image_to_volume, copy_volume_to_image)
we may end up with an attached volume that we don't cleanup.

This patch tries to detach the volume if we fail when validating the
device after we have attached the volume.

This happens for example on multipath when we have properly detected the
paths but they are all in a failed state when we try to read from the
device on validation.

Closes-Bug: #1502138
Change-Id: I73be4206930eba7da064e22d86ff2136191acb0b
"}]
commit_message:
Detach volume on device validation failure

If device validation fails when attaching a volume for some driver
operation (copy_volume_data, copy_image_to_volume, copy_volume_to_image)
we may end up with an attached volume that we don't cleanup.

This patch tries to detach the volume if we fail when validating the
device after we have attached the volume.

This happens for example on multipath when we have properly detected the
paths but they are all in a failed state when we try to read from the
device on validation.

Closes-Bug: #1502138
Change-Id: I73be4206930eba7da064e22d86ff2136191acb0b

commit_message:
Get rid of version.yaml facts

/etc/version.yaml is built together with ISO and
it is not a part of any rpm package which contradicts
package based approach.

This patch introduces 2 other puppet facts which
are from the following files:
- /etc/fuel_release
- /etc/fuel_openstack_version
These files are to be packaged into RPM packages and built
using perestroika. Besides, it assumes there is is
PRODUCTION variable in astute.yaml which is used
to set $production (by default it is 'docker').

Depends-On: I02f32386232c94a0288877dfc78513a8bc74d23e
Depends-On: I6e867c4e118518ad02425b49bb067738d4da20c4
Depends-On: I175dc620cbdff3959519e3fc374894f93bba45ac
Implements blueprint: docker-images-perestroika

Change-Id: I5f264fbc8f80a2e92920484ef6a6e28e6c8e7e58

commit_message:
Add checkpoint logging when terminating an instance

Following I6b9e7fc7b3a14ccf8b1531fa08ce8d732e23775a for building an
instance, this adds some checkpoint logging for terminating an instance,
including destroying it on the hypervisor, deallocating the network, and
detaching any volumes.

Related-Bug: #1500615

Change-Id: I16b8879f9dad9b0283b0758c41c70233624276f9

subject: Fix slorange on-disk format when including whole object
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-10-01 21:24:39.000000000', 'files': ['swift/common/middleware/slo.py', 'test/unit/common/middleware/test_slo.py'], 'message': "Fix slorange on-disk format when including whole object

Not that the current implementation is broken, just wasteful.

When a client specifies a range for an SLO segment that includes the
entire referenced object, we should drop the 'range' key from the
manifest that's stored on disk.

Previously, we would do this if the uploaded manifest included the
object-length for validation, but not if it didn't. Now we will
always drop the 'range' key if the entire segment is being used.

Change-Id: I69d2fff8c7c59b81e9e4777bdbefcd3c274b59a9
Related-Change: Ia21d51c2cef4e2ee5162161dd2c1d3069009b52c
"}]
commit_message:
Fix slorange on-disk format when including whole object

Not that the current implementation is broken, just wasteful.

When a client specifies a range for an SLO segment that includes the
entire referenced object, we should drop the 'range' key from the
manifest that's stored on disk.

Previously, we would do this if the uploaded manifest included the
object-length for validation, but not if it didn't. Now we will
always drop the 'range' key if the entire segment is being used.

Change-Id: I69d2fff8c7c59b81e9e4777bdbefcd3c274b59a9
Related-Change: Ia21d51c2cef4e2ee5162161dd2c1d3069009b52c

Output strings in POT files in the order of file locaiton

Keeping the order of strings same as in the original source document
helps translators find the sources and they can translate by checking
rendered contents :-)

Note that Zanata keeps the order of strings in uploaded POT files.

revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2015-10-01 19:49:32.000000000', 'files': ['nova/compute/manager.py'], 'message': "Add checkpoint logging when building an instance in compute manager

When the large ops job fails because instances timeout during the build,
it's hard to know what is going on for a given instance in the compute
manager's _do_build_and_run_instance flow since a lot of the trace
logging that happens is in the virt drivers.

The large ops job uses the fake virt driver which doesn't do much
logging at all. Rather than add logging to the fake virt driver, it'd be
useful to add some logging to the compute manager when we are doing
sub-tasks like building networks, building bdms, and spawning the instance
on the hypervisor.

Per: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards

The 'Starting instance' log message is changed to debug level and the
completed task logging unit of work messages with time spent are done at
info level.

Related-Bug: #1500615

Change-Id: I6b9e7fc7b3a14ccf8b1531fa08ce8d732e23775a
"}]
commit_message:
Add checkpoint logging when building an instance in compute manager

When the large ops job fails because instances timeout during the build,
it's hard to know what is going on for a given instance in the compute
manager's _do_build_and_run_instance flow since a lot of the trace
logging that happens is in the virt drivers.

The large ops job uses the fake virt driver which doesn't do much
logging at all. Rather than add logging to the fake virt driver, it'd be
useful to add some logging to the compute manager when we are doing
sub-tasks like building networks, building bdms, and spawning the instance
on the hypervisor.

Per: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards

The 'Starting instance' log message is changed to debug level and the
completed task logging unit of work messages with time spent are done at
info level.

Related-Bug: #1500615

Change-Id: I6b9e7fc7b3a14ccf8b1531fa08ce8d732e23775a

commit_message:
The option force_metadata=True breaks the dhcp agent

Patch I5f6ee9788717c3d4f1f2e2a4b9734fdd8dd92b40 has an issue with
force_metadata = True.

Using the option force_metadata=True while
enable_isolated_metadata=False (which is the default), will break the
dhcp agent because the variable subnet_to_interface_ip is being
referenced before assignment.

Co-Authored-By: Jakub Libosvar <jlibosva@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I4e1d918e3a24dd483ee134021f587ae4520bf431
Closes-Bug: #1499406

commit_message:
Ansible 2.0 compatibility

These changes allow the various playbooks to be executed by
Ansible 1.9.x and 2.0. This was necessary as 2.0 has a number
of changes to the YAML processor, and certain ways of doing
things have naturally had to change.

- Removed pass-through variable when a role is explicitly defined
  with variables passed through to it as updated yaml parser fails
  to handle appropriately.
- Defined a default dib_packages variable of an empty string.
- Changed stray boolean compare to use an is defined check as
  the the parser in Ansible 2.0 does not equate undefined to
  false.
- Explicitly defined the testing_user for the syntax check
  as the check fails without it.
- Revised MySQL module syntax usage to be compatible between
  Ansible 1.9.x and 2.0 development branches.
- Updated some conditionals making string compares with lookups

commit_message:
Fix value_meta length check

For vertica, the value_meta name/value pair is persisted in a
varchar(2048) column, so we need to include the json chars and
name in the field length check.  Very bad things happen if
metrics like this slip through to kafka and eventually the
persister, causing entire batches of metrics to never get
persisted.

Change-Id: I90d148000afbd9f48b3e33f0e66edea2114e14a3
Closes-Bug: #1501929

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-09-15 08:54:12.000000000', 'files': ['neutron/tests/functional/agent/linux/test_async_process.py'], 'message': "func: Don't use private method of AsyncProcess

In functional test we simulate crash of AsyncProcess by calling
_kill_process(). This method is a private method and such usage
introduced a race where process was respawned prior to calling wait() of
killed process, leading to infinite wait on newly spawned process.

This patch adds manual send of kill and then active waiting for process
to be respawned, similarly like done with recent keepalived patch [1].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/222460/7/neutron/tests/functional/agent/linux/test_keepalived.py

Closes-Bug: #1477860
Change-Id: I1c91393304d65a0695311416ecc5b64fd549b192
"}]
commit_message:
func: Don't use private method of AsyncProcess

In functional test we simulate crash of AsyncProcess by calling
_kill_process(). This method is a private method and such usage
introduced a race where process was respawned prior to calling wait() of
killed process, leading to infinite wait on newly spawned process.

This patch adds manual send of kill and then active waiting for process
to be respawned, similarly like done with recent keepalived patch [1].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/222460/7/neutron/tests/functional/agent/linux/test_keepalived.py

Closes-Bug: #1477860
Change-Id: I1c91393304d65a0695311416ecc5b64fd549b192

commit_message:
remove extra ceilometer devstack plugin declaration

The ceilometer devstack plugin was getting declared in project-config,
as well as by the ceilometer grenade plugin. This caused the
ceilometer project to be attempted to be run more than once. We should
probably protect against that, but we should also not declare it
twice. Especially as ceilometer is the first project to get all this
going, and it's configuration will likely be copied into others.

Change-Id: I9f083731b2ffe4a98cf7bfd5512a4aa3697af2fa

commit_message:
Fix CentOS detection

/etc/redhat-release on CentOS no longer contains the actual string
'CentOS'.  The contents are:

[jslagle@instack-rdo ~]$ cat /etc/redhat-release
Derived from Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7.1 (Source)

For reference:

[jslagle@instack-rdo ~]$ rpm -q centos-release
centos-release-7-1.1503.el7.centos.2.7.x86_64

This fixes the set-os-type script to handle this appropriately. Without
the fix, epel wasn't actually getting enabled when using tripleo.sh with
CentOS.

Change-Id: Id021e0ab91ce045196d4e3c3a34ef4d6ca9d08b5

commit_message:
Port test_netapp to Python 3

* Add close() method to FakeHttplibSocket,
  FakeDirectCmodeHTTPConnection, FakeDirect7modeHTTPConnection
* Replace StringIO() with BytesIO() for socket buffers
* makefile(): ignore optional arguments after mode
* Fix bytes versus Unicode: use bytes for HTTP body. Encode HTTP body
  to UTF-8 and HTTP headers to Latin1.
* tox.ini: add cinder.tests.unit.test_netapp to Python 3.4

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I3dc8c36a84ffbb47be3e85eed34518c6adad48ec

commit_message:
Fix rpc code due to neutron changes

The following commit: I6fea7f409c91b25d2c35b038d6100fdfa85d1905
Merged into neutron which changed how the rpc workers are started.
This patch updates the plugin so that dhcp and other services
that depend on neutrons rpcs work again.

commit_message:
Allow setting Agents description to None

Fix the validator for the 'description' attribute of Agents, allowing
it to be set to None.

Fix an API test that had two problems:
 1. It was not restoring the description to the agent it had updated
 2. It was retoring the description to '' instead of None.

Closes-Bug: #1466642

Change-Id: I50723e1346be0953d26216ba24907bac008ccfb6

commit_message:
devstack: Avoid modifying ERROR_ON_CLONE

As it's stated that it isn't acceptable to flip ERROR_ON_CLONE, [1]
follow the way OVN fetches its backend.
I.e. Use raw git commands directly.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-September/075355.html

Closes-Bug: #1502767
Change-Id: If88b689e6891479f36b8be7ac1cd75a748dba51d
(cherry picked from commit e2d7fd7d6440471c881a9e94c78cba7e1a7e69f6)

commit_message:
Implementation of api and engine classes

Murano API & Engine services provide the core of Murano.
This patch adds implementation of murano service manifests:
 * murano::api installs and manages Murano API service
   which processes user requests;
 * murano::engine installs and manages Murano Engine service
   which handles background request processing.

Change-Id: I6430544eda4fc6b1b16aa53ff9e6c127c62a2e5d

Currently after calling the cinderclient to create an image from a volume,
it also then tries to create another image. This fails as the keyword
volume is unexpected. This add checks so the image is not created in
this case. Allowing --volume to not throw an error when it has worked.

Closes-Bug: 1497221
'}]
commit_message:
Image fix bug with --volume

Currently after calling the cinderclient to create an image from a volume,
it also then tries to create another image. This fails as the keyword
volume is unexpected. This add checks so the image is not created in
this case. Allowing --volume to not throw an error when it has worked.

Change-Id: I67e650eb0b8c331d86515e3e326c39a5d6dad5e1
Closes-Bug: 1497221

revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2015-09-07 14:02:25.000000000', 'files': ['midonet/neutron/tests/unit/test_midonet_plugin_v2.py', 'midonet/neutron/plugin_v2.py'], 'message': 'Add port-security extension support

This patch enables the port-security neutron extension in midonet.
It also adds the changes required for the port-security database
management.

This neutron extension adds a new field to the PORT object:
port_security_enabled. This field is a boolean which will
have the following effects on a port depending on its value:

TRUE: Allow the creation of anti-spoof protection (including
allowed-address-pairs) and security groups on this port.

FALSE: Block the creation of allowed address pairs and
security groups on this port, and do not create any
anti-spoof protection for this port. Setting
port_security_enabled to False will fail if there are
security groups or allowed address pairs associated with
the port. Also, associating security groups or allowed
address groups with a port will fail if port_security_enabled
is set to false.

Change-Id: I49ace9cc437601353d6a90f8d6eca8a20ebf3dc6
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>
(cherry-picked from 61e3af412bb426695544025d0537f7792356b77b)
'}]
commit_message:
Add port-security extension support

This patch enables the port-security neutron extension in midonet.
It also adds the changes required for the port-security database
management.

This neutron extension adds a new field to the PORT object:
port_security_enabled. This field is a boolean which will
have the following effects on a port depending on its value:

TRUE: Allow the creation of anti-spoof protection (including
allowed-address-pairs) and security groups on this port.

FALSE: Block the creation of allowed address pairs and
security groups on this port, and do not create any
anti-spoof protection for this port. Setting
port_security_enabled to False will fail if there are
security groups or allowed address pairs associated with
the port. Also, associating security groups or allowed
address groups with a port will fail if port_security_enabled
is set to false.

Change-Id: I49ace9cc437601353d6a90f8d6eca8a20ebf3dc6
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>
(cherry-picked from 61e3af412bb426695544025d0537f7792356b77b)

commit_message:
Add second page (project)

This commit adds the second page to the app which shows detailed job
metrics from a specific project. To access this page user must click on
project name on home page.

For now the page is not acessing api method to get real data, but
a sample json created based on 'project_data.json' in mockups folder.

Change-Id: Ia257bb20f4a73a6e31ea98e1258dbe5fdd42c03d

commit_message:
If rescue failed set instance to ERROR

The compute API will allow attempting to rescue an instance that is in
active/stopped/error state.  The compute manager will power off the instance
before calling driver.rescue.

If the rescue call fails in the virt driver, we should set the instance
to ERROR state since we (1) know the instance is definitely not active since
the compute manager powered it off and (2) we don't know what failed in the
virt driver, so punting and putting the instance into ERROR state is better
than leaving it broken and not signaling that with the vm_state.

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>

Closes-Bug: 1418590
Change-Id: Ia1054d3f9193f876803f8b5a26d00bd9d5d66c12

commit_message:
Add optional parameter --resource-type to md-property-show

To retrieve list of properties in given namespace that is associated
to given resource type user can call e.g.
glance md-namespace-list --resource-type OS::Glance::Image
This will return properties with prefixes appended to their names.
However user can't call anything to show details of a property which
name includes resource type prefix.
This patch extends md-show-property with optional parameter
--resource-type. To retrieve property details user can call both, e.g.:
md-property-show cpu_cores
md-property-show --resource-type OS::Glance::Image hw_cpu_cores

Change-Id: Idf015abbcf8afd370d14c0495b97659d698f0a2e
Closes-Bug: #1367564
DocImpact
Co-Authored-By: Bartosz Fic <bartosz.fic@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Koniszewski <pawel.koniszewski@intel.com>

commit_message:
Introduce transactions to data seeding

Current implementation of glance-manage db metadefs-load/unload/export
commands don't use transactions. This may lead to problems with
e.g. loading json files to database, when code fails on properties
then user will have to manually remove related namespace from database.

To prevent such scenario data seeding script has been rewritten to
use sessions instead of engines. This gives possibility to do important
operations in transactions.

Change-Id: Id6e38c3d88eebc2a55b4db22a2f334706fb00e97
Closes-Bug: #1367729

commit_message:
Refactor reinstall and partition preservation tests

Follow changes were done in this patch:
- create cluster with controller + mongo instead of
  creating separate nodes for controller and mongo.
- reinstall_single_mongo_node test was deleted.
- merge mongo_partition_preservation and
  mysql_partition_preservation tests in
  mongo_mysql_partition_preservation test
- merge cinder_partition_preservation and
  nova_partition_preservation tests in
  cinder_nova_partition_preservation test.

Change-Id: I3a6612377ee7cdf7bcc71c0a1d13fba3923896c0
Closes-Bug:#1494768

meantime with this change.

commit_message:
Fix coverage configuration and execution

A number of configuration errors prevent the successful creation of code
coverage. This corrects the .coveragerc source/omit setup and the tox
package name generation.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/076193.html

Change-Id: If85385ac8b0817e9e5d167940ace37e733cacd41

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-09-09 09:00:43.000000000', 'files': ['deployment/puppet/neutron/manifests/server.pp'], 'message': 'Change DB max pool size to 50 for neutron-server

This patch fixes a regression caused by commit during synchronising upstream
Kilo puppet manifests to 7.0: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/189678/
(parameter database_max_pool_size was set to 10) but even in 5.0 we set
this parameter to 50 by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100859
And this is correct and confirmed again at the scale lab

Closes-Bug: #1493732
Change-Id: Ieef197baa2a6aff26aa8894b3dea2254a1272a2d
'}]
commit_message:
Change DB max pool size to 50 for neutron-server

This patch fixes a regression caused by commit during synchronising upstream
Kilo puppet manifests to 7.0: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/189678/
(parameter database_max_pool_size was set to 10) but even in 5.0 we set
this parameter to 50 by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100859
And this is correct and confirmed again at the scale lab

Closes-Bug: #1493732
Change-Id: Ieef197baa2a6aff26aa8894b3dea2254a1272a2d

commit_message:
Adapt Heat manifests for Liberty

- Switch to Librarian (using 7.0.0-mos-rc1 tag)
- Heat module doesn't contain custom patches
- Set rpc_response_timeout variable from heat class

Change-Id: I80c9265f0ce31ce3803894bd93416e648c0bd379
Related-bug: #1490469

commit_message:
Move nova module to librarian

This commit removes 'nova' module from fuel-library
and replaces it to be managed via librarian.
This commit uses 7.0.0-mos-rc1 tag of nova module.
This tag is intermediate stable state of
current master. Custom patches:
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11015/
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11020/
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11922/
https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/11017/
They are not merged in upstream master yet.

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I75b7464fb8040286a5f30395b08c50c529f4d50a

commit_message:
Adapt Neutron manifests for Liberty

- switch to Librarian (using 7.0.0-mos-rc1 tag)
- rename physnet_mtus to physical_network_mtus variable according to
  the upstream module
- set advertise_mtu option because in upstream it is disabled by default
- disable manage_vswitch for ovs-agent because bridges are handled
  by l23-network module
- use simpler grep in OCF scripts to satisfy execution strings with specific
  python versions (python, python2.7 and so on) - this may vary in packages
  (Debian, Ubuntu etc)

Change-Id: I855fdfe2d9d14fcc3150a7a83204d13865b9df10
Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

subject: Change ceilometer endpoint name from telemetry to metering
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-10-06 07:36:45.000000000', 'files': ['etc/pycadf/ceilometer_api_audit_map.conf'], 'message': "Change ceilometer endpoint name from telemetry to metering

The pycadf ceilometer api_audit_map.conf file currently refers
to ceilometer service_endpoint as telemetry and not as metering.
This is not aligned with the rest of the ceilometer community code.
The service_endpoint was named as telemetry initially assuming
the entire ceilometer code will switch to using it but that has not
happened yet. Thus, it's better to stick to metering for now.

Change-Id: I053177ef504989c4b9b367d671d47b00104600ab
Closes-Bug: 1501287
"}]
commit_message:
Change ceilometer endpoint name from telemetry to metering

The pycadf ceilometer api_audit_map.conf file currently refers
to ceilometer service_endpoint as telemetry and not as metering.
This is not aligned with the rest of the ceilometer community code.
The service_endpoint was named as telemetry initially assuming
the entire ceilometer code will switch to using it but that has not
happened yet. Thus, it's better to stick to metering for now.

Change-Id: I053177ef504989c4b9b367d671d47b00104600ab
Closes-Bug: 1501287

commit_message:
Ensure admin VIP does not conflict with another address

Because fuelweb_admin is a shared network all admin IPs
must be accounted for when finding a free IP for a VIP.
Previously only IPs assigned to nodes in clusters were
taken into account.

Change-Id: I0f1646ea2ceeaa5cd7b08743a309d5054e9f72f7
Closes-bug: #1501811

subject: type: Add retry to Exec resource
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-10-05 21:34:30.000000000', 'files': ['spec/defines/cinder_type_spec.rb', 'manifests/type.pp'], 'message': "type: Add retry to Exec resource

Cinder type needs to be created after Cinder API service start.
There is a race condition where the Exec can be run during Cinder API is
still trying to start.

If it's the case, the Exec will fail like this:
ERROR: Unable to establish connection to http://127.0.0.1:8776

This patch aims to retry another time after waiting 5 seconds, which is
a fair amount of time to wait for Cinder-API service.

Change-Id: I1c5caa00d87178d669d66736404e38214eed1ab6
"}]
commit_message:
type: Add retry to Exec resource

Cinder type needs to be created after Cinder API service start.
There is a race condition where the Exec can be run during Cinder API is
still trying to start.

If it's the case, the Exec will fail like this:
ERROR: Unable to establish connection to http://127.0.0.1:8776

This patch aims to retry another time after waiting 5 seconds, which is
a fair amount of time to wait for Cinder-API service.

Change-Id: I1c5caa00d87178d669d66736404e38214eed1ab6

commit_message:
[WIP] dvr: don't migrate fdb for snat devices

We use a single Port object to store a csnat device across multiple
nodes. During a router's setup, there's a case in which the port
changes to BUILD state and also switches a host (since the same single
Port is used), causing l2pop to delete some resources from the current
machine (like the tunneling device). This patch causes l2pop to not do
so in such cases.

Change-Id: I23b37ce74d9d53a44233a595ba3b7e419bb75112
Related-Bug: #1365473

revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-10-06 08:23:44.000000000', 'files': ['files/fuel-ha-utils/ocf/rabbitmq'], 'message': 'Make RabbitMQ OCF script tolerate rabbitmqctl timeouts

The change makes OCF script ignore small number of timeouts of rabbitmqctl
for 'heavy' operations: list_channels, get_alarms and list_queues.
Number of tolerated timeouts in a row is configured through a new variable
'max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts'. By default it is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl
timeouts are not tolerated at all.

Bug #1487517 is fixed by extracting declaration of local variables
'rc_alarms' and 'rc_queues' from assignment operations.

Text for Operations Guide:

If on node where RabbitMQ is deployed
other processes consume significant part of CPU, RabbitMQ starts
responding slow to queries by 'rabbitmqctl' utility. The utility is
used by RabbitMQ's OCF script to monitor state of the RabbitMQ.
When utility fails to return in pre-defined timeout, OCF script
considers RabbitMQ to be down and restarts it, which might lead to
a limited (several minutes) OpenStack downtime. Such restarts
are undesirable as they cause downtime without benefit. To
mitigate the issue, the OCF script might be told to tolerate
certain amount of rabbitmqctl timeouts in a row using the following
command:
  crm_resource --resource p_rabbitmq-server --set-parameter \
      max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts --parameter-value N

Here N should be replaced with the number of timeouts. For instance,
if it is set to 3, the OCF script will tolerate two rabbitmqctl
timeouts in a row, but fail if the third one occurs.

By default the parameter is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl timeout is not
tolerated at all. The downside of increasing the parameter is that
if a real issue occurs which causes rabbitmqctl timeout, OCF script
will detect that only after N monitor runs and so the restart, which
might fix the issue, will be delayed.

To understand that RabbitMQ's restart was caused by rabbitmqctl timeout
you should examine lrmd.log of the corresponding controller on Fuel
master node in /var/log/docker-logs/remote/ directory. Here lines like
"the invoked command exited 137: /usr/sbin/rabbitmqctl list_channels ..."

indicate rabbitmqctl timeout. The next line will explain if it
caused restart or not. For example:
"rabbitmqctl timed out 2 of max. 3 time(s) in a row. Doing nothing for now."

DocImpact: user-guide, operations-guide

Closes-Bug: #1479815
Closes-Bug: #1487517
Change-Id: I9dec06fc08dbeefbc67249b9e9633c8aab5e09ca
(cherry picked from commit 2707a5ebbff7012a94de77b60fd594f5bcb29e05)
'}]
commit_message:
Make RabbitMQ OCF script tolerate rabbitmqctl timeouts

The change makes OCF script ignore small number of timeouts of rabbitmqctl
for 'heavy' operations: list_channels, get_alarms and list_queues.
Number of tolerated timeouts in a row is configured through a new variable
'max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts'. By default it is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl
timeouts are not tolerated at all.

Bug #1487517 is fixed by extracting declaration of local variables
'rc_alarms' and 'rc_queues' from assignment operations.

Text for Operations Guide:

If on node where RabbitMQ is deployed
other processes consume significant part of CPU, RabbitMQ starts
responding slow to queries by 'rabbitmqctl' utility. The utility is
used by RabbitMQ's OCF script to monitor state of the RabbitMQ.
When utility fails to return in pre-defined timeout, OCF script
considers RabbitMQ to be down and restarts it, which might lead to
a limited (several minutes) OpenStack downtime. Such restarts
are undesirable as they cause downtime without benefit. To
mitigate the issue, the OCF script might be told to tolerate
certain amount of rabbitmqctl timeouts in a row using the following
command:
  crm_resource --resource p_rabbitmq-server --set-parameter \
      max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts --parameter-value N

Here N should be replaced with the number of timeouts. For instance,
if it is set to 3, the OCF script will tolerate two rabbitmqctl
timeouts in a row, but fail if the third one occurs.

By default the parameter is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl timeout is not
tolerated at all. The downside of increasing the parameter is that
if a real issue occurs which causes rabbitmqctl timeout, OCF script
will detect that only after N monitor runs and so the restart, which
might fix the issue, will be delayed.

To understand that RabbitMQ's restart was caused by rabbitmqctl timeout
you should examine lrmd.log of the corresponding controller on Fuel
master node in /var/log/docker-logs/remote/ directory. Here lines like
"the invoked command exited 137: /usr/sbin/rabbitmqctl list_channels ..."

indicate rabbitmqctl timeout. The next line will explain if it
caused restart or not. For example:
"rabbitmqctl timed out 2 of max. 3 time(s) in a row. Doing nothing for now."

DocImpact: user-guide, operations-guide

Closes-Bug: #1479815
Closes-Bug: #1487517
Change-Id: I9dec06fc08dbeefbc67249b9e9633c8aab5e09ca
(cherry picked from commit 2707a5ebbff7012a94de77b60fd594f5bcb29e05)

commit_message:
Add neutron-linuxbridge-cleanup util

Removal of empty bridges have been disabled [1] to fix a race condition
between Nova and Neutron where a bridge would be removed if
the only instance using it is rebooted. This means empty bridges
will pile up over time.

This script can be used to periodically remove empty bridges by running it
on compute nodes.

Note: Usage of this script can still trigger the original race condition.
It should be used when you don't expect anyone do be doing operations
on their instances.

[1] Commit 8dd8a7d93564168b98fa2350eedf56acede42b0f

DocImpact: Add neutron-linuxbridge-cleanup util
Related-bug: #1328546
Closes-bug: #1497027
Co-Authored-By: Cedric Brandily <zzelle@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Ieb2796381579ad295abf361ce483d979a53d2bd6

commit_message:
Fix too loose url regex for snapshot creation

Current regex '^(?P<instance_id>[^/]+)/create' for url
projects/images/<instance-id>/create will match all urls start with 'create' by
mistake. The '$' added will make sure the regex only match 'create' as expect.

Change-Id: I9f180d8d904d15e9458513f39b1e4719ac6800a3
Closes-Bug: #1477822

commit_message:
Port horizon utils tests to Python 3

* Use literal octal number syntax instead of the oct() function. The
  oct() function gives a different result on Python 2 and Python 3
  (Python 3 uses the "0o" prefix, not Python 2).
* format_value() explicitly cast the result to float. It's needed on
  Python 3 to cast a Decimal to float, because round(Decimal) returns a
  Decimal.
* tox.ini: run all horizon.test.tests.utils tests on Python 3.4

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: Ifd7c0e16ea85b691b81659acb010e9eb6f982d13

commit_message:
Port openstack dashboard overview tests to Python 3

* Fix CsvDataMixin: replace map() with a list-comprehension to get a
  list on Python 3, because the sequence is consumed more than once. On
  Python 3, map() returns an iterator which can only be consumed once.
* tox.ini: add openstack_dashboard.dashboards.project.overview.tests
  to Python 3.4.

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I9fb71a0b45c1e0a083c91476970938df5c649806

commit_message:
Update preview_update_stack to align with PATCH updates

Currently attempting to do a preview update call with PATCH fails,
because we didn't align the behavior of preview update with the
actual update in the recent additions to fix bug #1224828

So, refactor to ensure both preview_update & update use the same
code, and add a PATCH path to the update API.

Change-Id: I8ce5c0ea4035a7b9563db10ea10433e7f5f99a4f
Closes-Bug: #1501207
(cherry picked from commit 604595a39c9345d214f9f02c2ab8d7d1d768fcbe)

subject: Reduce frequency of logging environment resources
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-10-06 01:02:01.000000000', 'files': ['heat/engine/environment.py', 'heat/engine/resources/__init__.py', 'heat/engine/service.py'], 'message': 'Reduce frequency of logging environment resources

Currently we log all template resources every time any API call
happens which indirectly creates an Environment object, which
results in a lot of duplicate bloat in the heat logs (not even
at debug level..)

So, instead log all environment resources (e.g those from resource
plugins and the global environment) only when we start the
service, and log user-provided template resources only when we
do the template validation on create/update, for only the root stack,
because we pass a derived subset environment down to all children.

We also switch to using the string representation of the ResourceInfo
objects, as this contains a bit more useful info than the current
log format.

Change-Id: I20007c1ad6bf8b1479c1d60a5c392b8b9e1c06c4
Closes-Bug: #1499330
(cherry picked from commit 5d6234ecf64650b0eb7bd92eb530e899ff061457)
'}]
commit_message:
Reduce frequency of logging environment resources

Currently we log all template resources every time any API call
happens which indirectly creates an Environment object, which
results in a lot of duplicate bloat in the heat logs (not even
at debug level..)

So, instead log all environment resources (e.g those from resource
plugins and the global environment) only when we start the
service, and log user-provided template resources only when we
do the template validation on create/update, for only the root stack,
because we pass a derived subset environment down to all children.

We also switch to using the string representation of the ResourceInfo
objects, as this contains a bit more useful info than the current
log format.

Change-Id: I20007c1ad6bf8b1479c1d60a5c392b8b9e1c06c4
Closes-Bug: #1499330
(cherry picked from commit 5d6234ecf64650b0eb7bd92eb530e899ff061457)

The intention is to safely fail if we try to destroy a
non existing set, or delete a non existing member.
Otherwise the agent gets stuck in a loop if such situation
happens. Such kind of event would be logged as errors.

Change-Id: If67330523d114d6da13d0280851e7138a51d08f7
Closes-bug: #1497074

commit_message:
Execute ipset command using check_exit_code

When l2 agent execute ipset command, we should pass
parameter 'check_exit_code' to self.execute acording to
action.
The intention is to safely fail if we try to destroy a
non existing set, or delete a non existing member.
Otherwise the agent gets stuck in a loop if such situation
happens. Such kind of event would be logged as errors.

Change-Id: If67330523d114d6da13d0280851e7138a51d08f7
Closes-bug: #1497074

commit_message:
Automatic library concatenation

This patch removes the need for us to manually add each javascript
file to index.html to have it be included in the final deliverable.
Instead, our build script makes the assumption that every directory
in ./app/js/modules should be packaged into a single library.

Change-Id: I70b5d34c840745978f0ecd79b29c6b4ae7d87f4e
